ODE XIII.

It is supposed that Horace addressed this ode to Mark Antony, attho time he was ensnared by the love of Cleopatra, and was me'dltating an expedition with her against Italy, that he might make her mistress of the Roman empire, to dissuade him from that des- perate enterprise. Torrentius says, that he saw an ancient manu- script, in which the title of this ode was, Ad Alexandrum Paridem. And there is little doubt but a parallel is here intended between Paris and Antony3 each of whom embarked for his own country with a foreign queen, to the ruin of himself and those connected with him.
